      "content": "hey, i'm working on a storage engine component and need a basic LSM-tree implementation in python. i need it to handle a MemTable and flush to SSTables when it gets too full. \n\nhere's the test script i'm using to verify the logic. i need the code to pass all these assertions:\n\n```python\nimport unittest\n\nclass TestLSMTree(unittest.TestCase):\n    def test_basic_ops(self):\n        lsm = LSMTree(memtable_threshold=3)\n        lsm.put(\"a\", \"1\")\n        lsm.put(\"b\", \"2\")\n        lsm.put(\"c\", \"3\")\n        # this should trigger a flush\n        lsm.put(\"d\", \"4\") \n        \n        self.assertEqual(lsm.get(\"a\"), \"1\")\n        self.assertEqual(lsm.get(\"b\"), \"2\")\n        self.assertEqual(lsm.get(\"c\"), \"3\")\n        self.assertEqual(lsm.get(\"d\"), \"4\")\n\n    def test_persistence(self):\n        # verify that data survives even if memtable is cleared/flushed\n        lsm = LSMTree(memtable_threshold=2)\n        lsm.put(\"key1\", \"val1\")\n        lsm.put(\"key2\", \"val2\") # flush happens here\n        \n        # verify we can still get it\n        self.assertEqual(lsm.get(\"key1\"), \"val1\")\n        self.assertEqual(lsm.get(\"key2\"), \"val2\")\n\n    def test_delete(self):\n        lsm = LSMTree(memtable_threshold=5)\n        lsm.put(\"x\", \"100\")\n        lsm.delete(\"x\")\n        self.assertIsNone(lsm.get(\"x\"))\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    unittest.main()\n```\n\ncan you write the `LSMTree` class for me? i need the `put`, `get`, and `delete` methods implemented, plus the logic to handle the SSTable flushing. you can just mock the actual disk I/O for the SSTables for now, but the `get` needs to be able to find the data even after it moves from the MemTable to an SSTable.",
